  - The `element` parameter in `each()`'s callback is now `TElement` instead of `Element`
  - `promise()` overloads now return `JQuery.Promise<this>` instead of `JQuery.Promise<Element>`
  - Added tests for:
    - manipulation-related methods
    - queue-related methods
    - traversing-related methods
    - misc-related methods
- `JQueryStatic`
  - `each()` now has `this` typed
  - `error()`'s return type made more flexible (since `error()` is meant to be replaced)
  - `extend()` now returns `any` instead of an incorrect type when called with 6 or more additional objects
  - `get(settings)` and `post(settings)` now require `url`

  - Specified callback type for success status codes and standard error status codes
  - Parameters with type `ErrorTextStatus | null` are now just `ErrorTextStatus`

body:
Hello, 
I saw that it is impossible to assign a Duplex stream into a Readable stream because of the setEncoding prototype

- On internal.Readable the prototype is
`setEncoding(encoding: string): this;`
- On NodeJS.ReadableStream the prototype is
`setEncoding(encoding: string | null): this;`

The `isFSA` and `isError` checks are assertions, so they should declare their return value as an assertion.

However, one thing I wonder about the `ErrorAction` type is, `isError` makes _no guarantees_ that the `payload` is an `Error`. The spec even says that it SHOULD be an Error, but as it is analogous to a Promise rejection value, it can be anything.

I could change it to `extend Action<any>`, or change it to `ErrorAction<T = any> extends Action<T>` but that would be as-assertion-like, as the compiler would have to take the generic argument at face value.

```json
"test": "node node_modules/types-publisher/bin/tester/test.js --run-from-definitely-typed --nProcesses 1"
```

| 2 | 42 min 44 sec | 16 min 5 sec |
| 3 | 46 min 38 sec | 15 min 52 sec |
| 4 | 41 min 58 sec | 16 min 57 sec |

<sub>`master` was at https://github.com/leonard-thieu/DefinitelyTyped/commit/f2c8b617014491a302a9d7a01d83bbde3366dc0d when these tests were run</sub>

Is there any pitfalls from bumping up `--nProcesses`?
